      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>LEAD: To the Sports Editor:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>Has nature stolen a base on America? (Or have the Russians?) Perhaps it is time to commission a national scientific inquiry into the great 1987 home run debate.</p>
        <p>If the Kremlin has devised some subtle, inchmeal way to undermine the United States by rarefying our atmosphere, might not a lessened air resistance to the batted ball be the first measurable evidence of such.</p>
        <p>Or possibly those pinholes in the ozone layer are to blame. Could excess doses of ultra violet be spawning all of reports of UFO's hovering near stadiums, or the after-effect of Chernobyl on air density, or emanations from decade-old Astroturf?</p>
        <p>Or - sadly - is it something so rudimentary as team owners and ballmakers conspiring, in one low blow, to juice up the horsehide, gate receipts and positive cash flow?</p>
        <p>''Homeric questions to be sure,'' mused the battered southpaw as he made his way to the showers.</p>
        <p>LEO KALTMAN</p>
        <p>Forest Hills, Queens</p>
      </block>
